Okay, I hung the new nest box today. This is how it looks in its new place in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one is asking: "What exactly is in there?"
Above is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fisheye lens and an IR LED, which I got from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swivel side wall of the nest box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
In the gray box hanging on the side of the nesting box, the battery is located.
Once it is charged, I have a runtime of about 4 hours.
I'll call that a feature. This way, the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure whether the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points that I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
That's almost a pity, because I had planned to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof and point it downwards into the garden.
Maybe I will do that still, if I set up more nesting boxes with cameras. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I probably need that.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It only turned off an hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery stopped charging three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or slightly less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I guess I have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
In general, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
