It turned out that on the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the power supply, the 5 V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen.
I swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lit.
The ESP did not go online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and he is still offline.
It looks like he's doing a restart and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel is just not worth anything. I've ordered a larger one now and hope that one will work.
Look what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and is partially obscured by a tree) that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I switch the device on.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if this setup is sufficient or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021 and it is supposed to deliver 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or with my multimeter, or the data have been altered.
Good news!
